\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The popular notion that the COVID-19 pandemic has been \'93good for the environment\'94\'97that nature is recovering while humanity stays at home\'97 appeals to many people grasping for some upside to the global tragedy. Reality, though, may not cooperate with such hopes.\
The benefits many found heartening early on\'97from cleaner air to birdsong newly audible as cars and planes went quiet\'97were always likely to be temporary. And with lockdowns easing, they have already begun to dissipate. Now, some experts fear that the world risks a future with more traffic, more pollution, and climate change that worsens faster than ever. It\'92s too soon to know whether that gloomy scenario will play out, but concerning signs seem to be growing all around the world.\
In early April, with shutdowns widespread, daily global carbon emissions were {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41558-020-0797-x"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 down by 17 percent}} compared to last year. But as of June 11, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.icos-cp.eu/gcp-covid19"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 new data}} show that they are only about 5 percent lower than at the same point in 2019, even though normal activity has not yet fully restarted.\
\'93We still have the same cars, the same roads, the same industries, same houses,\'94 says {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tyndall.ac.uk/people/corinne-le-qu%C3%A9r%C3%A9"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 Corinne Le Qu\'e9r\'e9}}, professor of climate change at the University of East Anglia in Britain and lead author of the original study and subsequent update. \'93So as soon as the restrictions are released, we go right back to where we were.\'94\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
